          "title": "The call to return and its eschatological horizon (31:6-7)",
          "body": "After five verses of theological argument, Isaiah delivers one imperative: 'Return to Him from whom you have deeply defected, O sons of Israel.' The Hebrew 'amaq' (deeply) indicates the defection has not been casual — it has been profound, comprehensive, and long-standing. The call to return is the chapter's pastoral heart, and it connects the doctrinal argument of verses 1-5 to the practical outcome of verses 7-9. Repentance is not abstract: verse 7 describes its visible form — 'in that day every man will cast away his silver idols and his gold idols, which your sinful hands have made for you as a sin.' The 'that day' formula (bayom hahu) opens an eschatological horizon beyond the immediate Assyrian crisis. Commentators divide over whether verse 7 describes repentance at the historical deliverance of 701 BC (John Oswalt, NICOT) or a future comprehensive turning (J. Alec Motyer, Tyndale OT Commentary). Both may be true — the immediate crisis is a type of the final day, and the repentance Isaiah calls for in 701 BC anticipates the national repentance that Zechariah 12:10 and Romans 11:26 project to the end of the age. Importantly, the idols are identified as the work of 'sinful hands' — the makers are implicated in the objects they made. Idolatry is not neutral religious expression but sin, and abandoning it is not cultural preference but moral necessity."
