        "title": "Return — the imperative the argument demands",
        "range": "31:6-7",
        "excerpt": "Return to Him from whom you have deeply defected, O sons of Israel.",
        "body": "After five verses of theological argument — accusation, ontological proof, divine similes — Isaiah narrows to a single word: 'Return.' The Hebrew *shuv* (implied by the call, whose explicit term is *sarah*, defection) is the Old Testament's comprehensive word for repentance — the turning of the whole person back toward God. It is not primarily an emotional term but a directional one: you have been facing Egypt, and God is calling you to turn your face back toward Him.\n\nThe adverb 'deeply' (*amaq*) intensifies the indictment. This is not a recent lapse or a situational compromise; the defection has been thoroughgoing and extended. The same verb *amaq* is used in Psalm 64:6 of plans 'deeply devised' — the image is of depth, of something that has gone far down. Judah's turning away from the Lord has been comprehensive, structural, long-practiced. The call to return is correspondingly comprehensive, not merely tactical adjustment.\n\nVerse 7 describes what genuine return looks like in concrete terms: 'in that day every man will cast away his silver idols and his gold idols, which your sinful hands have made for you as a sin.' The *elilim* (idols, literally 'worthless things') are specified by material — silver (*keseph*) and gold (*zahav*) — pointing to the economic investment and craftsman effort behind them. They were made by 'sinful hands' and designated 'a sin' — Isaiah does not soften the moral category. True repentance has a visible, physical expression: the idol does not simply lose its psychological grip; it is *cast away*.\n\nThe 'that day' (*bayom hahu*) formula opens a dual temporal horizon that commentators have read differently. John Oswalt (NICOT, 1998) argues the primary reference is the historical deliverance of 701 BC, when Sennacherib's withdrawal prompted a moment of covenantal renewal under Hezekiah (2 Chronicles 32:23). J. Alec Motyer (Tyndale OTC, 1993) sees the eschatological horizon as primary, reading this alongside the 'that day' passages of Isaiah 2:20 (where the same language of casting away idols of silver and gold appears verbatim) and projecting it to the final restoration of Israel. Both readings are canonically warranted — the immediate historical event functions as a type and down-payment of the eschatological reality, consistent with Isaiah's characteristic use of near-far prophetic fulfillment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Amaq sarah* — 'deeply defected,' from *amaq* (to go deep) and *sarah* (to turn aside, rebel). *Elilim* — 'nothings, worthless things,' the contemptuous word for idols; plural of *elil*, from a root meaning 'weak, worthless.' *Bayom hahu* — Isaiah's eschatological formula, used 16 times in chapters 2–27 alone."
